<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1325,873,1899]" lastBlockId="2.[264,1325,284,430]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
DIAGNOSIS ­ 
<taxonomicName box="[500,749,1794,1819]" class="Insecta" family="Trichogrammatidae" genus="Trichogramma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bertii">
<emphasis box="[500,749,1794,1819]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Trichogramma bertii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is best characterized by the very short flagelliform setae and the relatively elongate intervolsellar process. 
<taxonomicName box="[984,1078,1833,1859]" class="Insecta" family="Trichogrammatidae" genus="Trichogramma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bertii">
<emphasis box="[984,998,1834,1859]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1014,1078,1834,1859]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">bertii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Trichogrammatidae" genus="Trichogramma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exiguum">
<emphasis box="[1234,1248,1834,1859]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">exiguum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and to 
<taxonomicName box="[433,589,1873,1899]" class="Insecta" family="Trichogrammatidae" genus="Trichogramma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pretiosum">
<emphasis box="[433,447,1874,1899]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[473,589,1874,1899]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">pretiosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs by the much shorter flagelliform setae and intervolsellar process with its pointed apex attaining the same level as the apex of the dorsal lamina or extending slightly beyond it.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
